-- Equities in South Africa Advance for Fourth Day in Five, Led by Richemont
-- B y   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n   a n d   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-03T16:28:42Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-03/south-african-stocks-advance-for-a-fourth-day-in-five-led-up-by-richemont.html
South Africa’s benchmark  FTSE/JSE
Africa All Share Index  rose for the fourth time in five days,
adding 208.34, or 0.7 percent, to 30,817.97 by the 5 p.m. close
in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Aquarius Platinum Ltd.  (AQP SJ), the world’s fourth-largest
producer of the metal, fell 22 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 41.26
rand, the biggest drop since Oct. 22. Platinum retreated for the
first day in five, losing as much as 1.7 percent to $1,689.72 an
ounce.  Coal of Africa Ltd.  (CZA SJ), an explorer of the fuel,
retreated for a fifth day, losing 1.54 rand, or 16 percent, to 8
rand, the steepest decline in more than two years. The company
said it was given until Nov. 11 to comply with South African
environmental regulations at its Mooiplaats colliery, according
to a regulatory filing.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-largest
producer of the metal, slipped 4 rand, or 2 percent, to 195
rand, the lowest since Oct. 28. Workers at the company plan to
hold a day of mourning at all operations following the death of
a worker in an accident at Impala’s No. 11 shaft, the National
Union of Mineworkers said.  Cie Financiere Richemont SA  (CFR SJ), the world’s largest
jewelry maker, advanced for a second day, rising 1.02 rand, or
2.9 percent, to 36.17 rand, the highest since at least August
1990, when Bloomberg began tracking the shares. Richemont was
raised to “outperform” from “underperform” at CA Cheuvreux.  Imperial Holdings Ltd.  (IPL SJ), South Africa’s largest
auto dealer, climbed 2.18 rand, or 1.8 percent, to 123.48 rand,
the highest close since May 2007. Chief Executive Officer  Hubert Brody  said the company will use the 742 million-rand ($108
million) acquisition of subsidiary CIC Holdings Ltd. to expand
its business in the rest of Africa.  Sekunjalo Investments Ltd.  (SKJ SJ), an investment group,
increased 4 cents, or 8.7 percent, to 50 cents, the highest
since April 2009. The company said net income from continuing
operations was 10.3 million rand in the six months through
August from a loss of 58.1 million rand a year earlier,
according to a stock-exchange filing.  To contact the reporters on this story:
